  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Translingual writing is the practice and theory of composing across and between languages, dialects, and registers — treating linguistic diversity as a resource for meaning-making rather than a problem to be corrected.\nSuresh Canagarajah argues that all communication is translingual: speakers and writers always draw on multiple linguistic resources (languages, dialects, registers, codes) and negotiate meaning across differences. The monolingual assumption — that \u0026ldquo;good writing\u0026rdquo; means writing in one consistent, standard language — distorts how we understand composing and excludes writers whose linguistic repertoires don\u0026rsquo;t match the dominant standard [@canagarajah2013].\n",
